flowRoot.flowPara: Section titles are bold 64pt text, while this section text is 40pt. The font is TexGyre Schola, which is inspired by Century Schoolbook. The blue boxes are page guides (delete or hide them before printing) and the purple boxes are section guides. Ideally each column will have 1-2 sections and at least one image or other visual.

The section title is vertically centered in its box, and left-aligned. This text is flowed into its frame and justified. The section frame is aligned to the bottom of the title frame, and they're both aligned with the right edge of the column frame.

In Inkscape you can flow text into multiple frames by selecting the text and then the frames, selecting the first frame last. That's how this text flows across two columns. For bullet points you'll have to improvise.

Use File->Import to add images. Each column is 10 inches wide, and you can set the image width while locking the aspect ratio. Then just align the top of the image with the bottom of the text box above it.

To lay out a new section, first select the title box of an existing section (F1 for select tool), and use Ctrl-D to dupicate it (don't use Ctrl-C/Ctrl-V, because that can convert a rectangle into an image). Place it where you want the section to start, then duplicate a text box and place that bleow it using the align and distribute tools. Next duplicate the section title and align it into the box you made for it, and then edit it (F8 for text tool) to the title you want. Finally, duplicate the text of another section, and move it near where you want it to go. Select the box for the text along with the text, and choose Text->Flow into Frame from the menu (Alt-W). If the text gets too long, select the frame and edit its height. You'll need to re-align the frame vertically afterwards.
